# Wiring Obsidian to Claude

With the goal of creating a "2nd Brain", I downloaded Obsidian in summer of '25 and spent weeks trying to make it work with ChatGPT using n8n and a stack of webhooks. This went very poorly, with ChatGPT even gently suggesting n8n was over my head (ChatGPT was right). In February '26 I installed Claude Desktop and tried again. Chat mode made it work. In March '26 I switched to Code mode and spent the next month building an operating system to outsource the things my ADHD brain does poorly.

Most of that time was spent hitting walls, building inefficient solutions, and constantly rewiring. Below is the setup I landed on, written up so you don't have to repeat my month of usage limits and iteration. Save your hours for your actual work.

## For the human reading this

**Claude Desktop is the app.** Inside it are three modes:

- **Chat**: conversation. You ask, Claude answers.
- **Cowork**: Claude sees what you're working on and helps in real time.
- **Code**: Claude does the work itself. Runs commands, edits files, follows protocols like `/start` and `/wrap`, schedules tasks.

All three modes can read and write your Obsidian vault. Only Code mode can run the automation and scheduled tasks covered later in this doc.

**To use this doc:** drop it into Claude Desktop's Code mode and say "do this." Claude reads the instructions below and handles the wiring. You'll click some buttons in Obsidian and paste a config file. That's your part. If something breaks, paste the error back to Claude and keep going.

Two things to know before you start:

- You need Obsidian installed and a vault created. A vault is just a folder of markdown notes that Obsidian reads. If you don't have one, make an empty folder and point Obsidian at it.
- Some of this needs Node.js and Python. Don't pre-install random versions. Let Claude tell you what's needed.

Below the line is Claude's operating manual. Keep reading only if you're curious.

